ضيف هي الاسئلة chapter 6 <html lang="en"><head><base target="_blank">


    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Chapter 7: The Axial Skeleton - Clinical Examination (100 Questions)</title>
    <style>
        /* Global and Layout Styles */
        body {
            font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; 
            background-color: #f8f9fa;
            padding: 20px;
            direction: ltr; 
        }

        .container {
            max-width: 1000px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            background-color: #ffffff;
            padding: 40px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0 5px 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }

        /* Header Styles */
        h1 {
            color: #1f3f66;
            text-align: center;
            border-bottom: 5px solid #00a896;
            padding-bottom: 15px;
            margin-bottom: 40px;
            font-weight: 700;
            font-size: 2.2em;
        }

        p.instructions {
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 30px;
            font-size: 1.1em;
            color: #6c757d;
        }

        /* Question Box Styles */
        .question-box {
            margin-bottom: 30px;
            padding: 25px;
            border: 1px solid #dee2e6;
            border-radius: 8px;
            background-color: #ffffff;
        }

        /* Question Text and Options */
        .question-text {
            font-size: 1.15em;
            color: #343a40;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            font-weight: 600;
            line-height: 1.5;
            text-align: left;
        }

        .option-label {
            display: block;
            background-color: #f8f9fa;
            padding: 14px;
            margin: 10px 0;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border: 1px solid #ced4da;
            transition: background-color 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
            text-align: left;
        }

        .option-label:hover {
            background-color: #e9f0f3;
            box-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
        }

        input[type="radio"] {
            margin-right: 10px; 
            transform: scale(1.1);
            accent-color: #1f3f66;
        }

        /* Submission Button and Result Area */
        .submission-area {
            text-align: center;
            margin-top: 40px;
        }

        #submit-btn {
            padding: 15px 30px;
            background-color: #00a896;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 8px;
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 1.2em;
            font-weight: bold;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }

        #submit-btn:hover {
            background-color: #008779;
        }

        #results {
            margin-top: 30px;
            padding: 30px;
            border: 2px solid #1f3f66;
            border-radius: 10px;
            background-color: #e9ecef;
            display: none;
            text-align: left;
        }

        #results h2 {
            color: #1f3f66;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            border-bottom: 2px dashed #adb5bd;
            padding-bottom: 10px;
        }

        .score-display {
            font-size: 1.5em;
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #00a896;
        }

        /* Feedback after submission */
        .explanation {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            border-left: 5px solid; 
            border-right: none;
            display: none;
            font-size: 0.95em;
            text-align: left;
        }

        .explanation.correct {
            border-color: #28a745;
            background-color: #d4edda;
            color: #155724;
        }

        .explanation.incorrect {
            border-color: #dc3545;
            background-color: #f8d7da;
            color: #721c24;
        }

        .correct-term {
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #1f3f66;
        }

        .result-summary {
            margin-top: 15px;
            font-size: 1.1em;
            text-align: left;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <h1>Chapter 7: The Axial Skeleton - Clinical Examination (100 Questions)</h1>
    <p class="instructions">Please select the best answer for each question. Your score will be calculated upon submission. This quiz is based on advanced clinical and anatomical references.</p>

    <form id="quiz-form">

        <div class="question-box" id="q1">
            <div class="question-text">1. A 45-year-old patient presents with acute pain radiating down the left leg (sciatica) after lifting a heavy object. Neurological examination reveals diminished ankle dorsiflexion (foot drop). Which axial skeleton pathology is most likely responsible for these symptoms?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="a"> Atlanto-axial subluxation</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="b" data-correct="true"> Lumbar disc herniation (L4-L5 or L5-S1)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="c"> Cervical spondylosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="d"> Thoracic outlet syndrome</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp1">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Sciatica (radiating pain), especially following heavy lifting, combined with specific motor deficits (like foot drop), is the classic clinical presentation of a <span class="correct-term">Lumbar disc herniation</span>, where the nucleus pulposus impinges on a spinal nerve root.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q2">
            <div class="question-text">2. During a pediatric check-up, a physician notices the anterior fontanelle is bulging and tense. This finding is a key clinical sign for which of the following conditions affecting the cranial bones?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="a"> Craniosynostosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="b" data-correct="true"> Increased Intracranial Pressure (e.g., Hydrocephalus)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="c"> Simple skull fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="d"> Paget's disease of the skull</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp2">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The fontanelles, which are areas of unossified fibrous tissue between the skull bones, serve as a pressure-release valve in infants. A bulging, tense anterior fontanelle is a classic sign of <span class="correct-term">Increased Intracranial Pressure</span>, often due to conditions like Hydrocephalus.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q3">
            <div class="question-text">3. A patient sustains a 'blowout fracture' of the orbit after blunt trauma. The orbital wall most commonly fractured, often leading to entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle and double vision, is composed primarily of which bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q3" value="a"> Zygomatic bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q3" value="b"> Frontal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q3" value="c" data-correct="true"> Maxilla (Orbital Floor)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q3" value="d"> Sphenoid bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp3">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The orbital floor is the thinnest wall of the orbit and is mostly formed by the <span class="correct-term">Maxilla</span>. Blunt trauma often causes the pressure inside the orbit to fracture this floor, allowing orbital contents to herniate into the maxillary sinus.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q4">
            <div class="question-text">4. To safely perform a Lumbar Puncture (spinal tap) in an adult, the needle must be inserted below the termination of the spinal cord (conus medullaris). Which vertebral interspace is the most common and safest landmark for this procedure?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q4" value="a"> Between C7 and T1</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q4" value="b"> Between T12 and L1</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q4" value="c" data-correct="true"> Between L3 and L4 or L4 and L5</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q4" value="d"> Between S1 and S2</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp4">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> In adults, the spinal cord typically ends around the L1/L2 level. Inserting the needle at the <span class="correct-term">L3/L4 or L4/L5 interspace</span> ensures the needle passes through the cauda equina, minimizing the risk of spinal cord injury.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q5">
            <div class="question-text">5. Severe, progressive scoliosis (lateral curvature of the spine) is often associated with a rib hump. Clinically, what is the most serious potential complication of severe thoracic scoliosis, regardless of the cause?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q5" value="a"> Chronic Carpal Tunnel Syndrome</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q5" value="b" data-correct="true"> Restrictive pulmonary disease (Impaired lung function)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q5" value="c"> Mandibular joint dysfunction</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q5" value="d"> Exaggerated Lumbar Lordosis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp5">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Severe lateral curvature (Scoliosis) of the thoracic spine significantly deforms the rib cage, restricting its movement. This leads to reduced lung volume and chest wall compliance, resulting in <span class="correct-term">Restrictive pulmonary disease</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q6">
            <div class="question-text">6. The Sternal Angle (Angle of Louis) is a crucial anatomical landmark on the axial skeleton. Which of the following structures or planes can be located by palpating this angle?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q6" value="a"> The articulation of the 1st rib with the sternum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q6" value="b" data-correct="true"> The junction between the Manubrium and the Body of the Sternum and the 2nd costal cartilage</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q6" value="c"> The xiphoid process and the costal margin</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q6" value="d"> The level of the diaphragm</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp6">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Sternal Angle</span> marks the boundary between the manubrium and the body of the sternum and is the anatomical point of reference for the second costal cartilage, which is used to count all other ribs.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q7">
            <div class="question-text">7. An elderly woman with advanced osteoporosis falls and sustains a wedge-shaped deformation of a vertebral body, most commonly in the thoracic region. This is referred to clinically as a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q7" value="a"> Burst fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q7" value="b"> Hangman's fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q7" value="c" data-correct="true"> Compression fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q7" value="d"> Jefferson fracture</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp7">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> A <span class="correct-term">Compression fracture</span> occurs when the vertebral body collapses, typically into a wedge shape, and is the most common type of fracture associated with low-energy trauma in patients with osteoporosis.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q8">
            <div class="question-text">8. Spina bifida is a congenital defect of the vertebral column. Which anatomical component of the vertebrae fails to fuse midline during embryonic development, leading to the condition?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q8" value="a"> The centrum (body)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q8" value="b" data-correct="true"> The vertebral laminae and spinous processes</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q8" value="c"> The transverse processes</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q8" value="d"> The pedicles</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp8">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Spina bifida results from the incomplete closure of the neural tube and the subsequent failure of the two halves of the <span class="correct-term">vertebral laminae and spinous processes</span> to fuse in the midline, leaving the spinal cord vulnerable.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q9">
            <div class="question-text">9. Following severe head trauma, clear fluid leakage from the ear (otorrhea) is highly suggestive of a fracture involving which complex region of the axial skeleton, often leading to a cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leak?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q9" value="a"> The orbital plate of the frontal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q9" value="b"> The mastoid process</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q9" value="c" data-correct="true"> The petrous part of the temporal bone (Middle Cranial Fossa)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q9" value="d"> The dens of the axis (C2)</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp9">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> CSF otorrhea occurs when a fracture involves the <span class="correct-term">petrous part of the temporal bone</span>, which houses the middle and inner ear structures and forms part of the cranial base, allowing CSF to leak into the ear canal.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q10">
            <div class="question-text">10. An elderly patient with Rheumatoid Arthritis has an unstable neck due to erosion of ligaments at the craniovertebral junction. This instability places the patient at high risk for displacement of the dens (odontoid process) of the Axis. This structure is an anatomical landmark on which vertebra?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q10" value="a"> C1 (Atlas)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q10" value="b" data-correct="true"> C2 (Axis)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q10" value="c"> T1</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q10" value="d"> The Occipital Bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp10">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Dens, or odontoid process, is the superior projection from the body of the <span class="correct-term">Axis (C2)</span>. It articulates with the anterior arch of the Atlas (C1), providing the pivot point for head rotation. Ligament erosion in conditions like RA can cause instability (subluxation) between C1 and C2.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q11">
            <div class="question-text">11. A patient involved in a rear-end car collision experiences hyperextension followed by hyperflexion of the neck. This mechanism often leads to a 'whiplash' injury, primarily affecting which section of the axial skeleton?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q11" value="a"> Thoracic spine</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q11" value="b"> Lumbar spine</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q11" value="c" data-correct="true"> Cervical spine</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q11" value="d"> Sacrum</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp11">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Whiplash</span> is the common term for a soft tissue injury (ligaments, muscles) of the neck, caused by rapid acceleration/deceleration, specifically impacting the <span class="correct-term">Cervical spine</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q12">
            <div class="question-text">12. A mother brings her infant for evaluation, noting that the baby's head is persistently tilted to one side and rotated to the opposite side. This condition, often due to injury or tightness of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, is clinically known as:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q12" value="a"> Kyphosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q12" value="b" data-correct="true"> Torticollis (Wry neck)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q12" value="c"> Plagiocephaly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q12" value="d"> Spondylitis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp12">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Torticollis</span>, or wry neck, is a condition where the head is twisted to one side, caused by a shortening of the neck muscles, most commonly the sternocleidomastoid.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q13">
            <div class="question-text">13. A patient presents with a fracture of the pars interarticularis of the Axis (C2) with traumatic spondylolisthesis. This clinically relevant fracture, often caused by hyperextension and vertical compression, is termed a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q13" value="a"> Jefferson fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q13" value="b"> Clay-Shoveler's fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q13" value="c" data-correct="true"> Hangman's fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q13" value="d"> Chance fracture</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp13">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Hangman's fracture</span> is a specific fracture involving the pedicles/pars interarticularis of C2, with displacement of C2 on C3, and is notoriously unstable.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q14">
            <div class="question-text">14. A diving accident victim sustains a burst fracture involving the anterior and posterior arches of the Atlas (C1). This fracture, caused by an axial load (compression), is commonly known as a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q14" value="a"> Odontoid fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q14" value="b" data-correct="true"> Jefferson fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q14" value="c"> Teardrop fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q14" value="d"> Burst fracture of C3</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp14">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> A <span class="correct-term">Jefferson fracture</span> is a comminuted fracture of the C1 (Atlas) ring, resulting from an axial load applied to the head (e.g., diving into shallow water).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q15">
            <div class="question-text">15. A young athlete complains of chronic lower back pain, especially during hyperextension. An X-ray reveals a bilateral fracture in the pars interarticularis of L5, leading to anterior slippage of L5 over the sacrum. This condition is known as:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q15" value="a"> Spondylosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q15" value="b"> Spinal stenosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q15" value="c" data-correct="true"> Spondylolisthesis (secondary to Spondylolysis)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q15" value="d"> Scheuermann’s disease</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp15">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Spondylolisthesis</span> is the anterior displacement of one vertebra over the one below it, often caused by <span class="correct-term">Spondylolysis</span> (a defect/stress fracture in the pars interarticularis).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q16">
            <div class="question-text">16. A diabetic patient presents with fever and localized back pain. Imaging shows destruction and collapse of a single vertebral body, commonly caused by a bacterial infection. What is the clinical term for this bone infection?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q16" value="a"> Osteoarthritis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q16" value="b" data-correct="true"> Osteomyelitis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q16" value="c"> Osteomalacia</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q16" value="d"> Discitis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp16">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Osteomyelitis</span> is a bone infection, and when it affects the spine (vertebral osteomyelitis), it can lead to destruction and collapse of the vertebral body.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q17">
            <div class="question-text">17. Kyphosis (exaggerated thoracic curvature) is commonly observed in elderly individuals. As noted in the textbook (Section 7.25), this is often associated with which underlying bone disease?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q17" value="a"> Osteopetrosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q17" value="b"> Paget's disease</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q17" value="c" data-correct="true"> Advanced osteoporosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q17" value="d"> Marfan syndrome</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp17">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The text states: "<span class="correct-term">Kyphosis is common in individuals with advanced osteoporosis</span>" (Section 7.25), due to vertebral compression fractures in the thoracic region.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q18">
            <div class="question-text">18. A physician needs to obtain a bone marrow sample for diagnosis. The sternum is often chosen as a biopsy site because of its accessibility and the relatively large amount of hematopoietic (red) marrow. Which part of the sternum is typically targeted?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q18" value="a"> Xiphoid process</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q18" value="b"> Sternal angle</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q18" value="c" data-correct="true"> Manubrium or body of the sternum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q18" value="d"> Clavicular notch</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp18">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Manubrium or body of the sternum</span> provides a relatively large, flat area close to the surface, making it an ideal site for bone marrow aspiration.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q19">
            <div class="question-text">19. An older patient reports increasing leg pain, cramping, and numbness when walking, which is relieved by sitting down or leaning forward (flexion). This clinical presentation is highly characteristic of:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q19" value="a"> Sciatica from Piriformis Syndrome</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q19" value="b" data-correct="true"> Lumbar Spinal Stenosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q19" value="c"> Tarsal Tunnel Syndrome</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q19" value="d"> Acute Disc Herniation</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp19">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Spinal Stenosis</span> is the narrowing of the vertebral canal, which compresses the neural elements. Symptoms are typically positional (worsened by extension, relieved by flexion/leaning forward).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q20">
            <div class="question-text">20. Spina bifida, a neural tube defect where the vertebral arches fail to form, is strongly linked to the deficiency of which vitamin or nutrient during embryonic development (Section 7.26)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q20" value="a"> Vitamin D</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q20" value="b" data-correct="true"> Folic Acid (Vitamin B9)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q20" value="c"> Calcium</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q20" value="d"> Vitamin A</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp20">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The text states: "<span class="correct-term">Deficiency of folic acid is associated with spina bifida</span>" (Section 7.26). Folic acid supplementation is crucial before and during early pregnancy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q21">
            <div class="question-text">21. The 11th and 12th ribs (floating ribs) lack attachment to the sternum. Clinically, a fracture of these ribs should raise suspicion for injury to which nearby abdominal organs?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q21" value="a"> Liver and Stomach</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q21" value="b" data-correct="true"> Spleen (left) and Kidneys (bilateral)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q21" value="c"> Appendix and Cecum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q21" value="d"> Bladder and Small Intestine</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp21">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Due to their position protecting the upper posterior abdominal viscera, fractures of the floating ribs (especially 11 and 12) can penetrate and damage the underlying <span class="correct-term">spleen</span> (left side) or the <span class="correct-term">kidneys</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q22">
            <div class="question-text">22. Following severe blunt trauma to the chest, a patient exhibits paradoxical movement (inward during inspiration, outward during expiration) of a segment of the chest wall. This is the hallmark sign of which life-threatening condition?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q22" value="a"> Pneumothorax</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q22" value="b" data-correct="true"> Flail Chest</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q22" value="c"> Costochondritis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q22" value="d"> Tension Pneumothorax</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp22">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Flail Chest</span> occurs when three or more adjacent ribs are fractured in two or more places, creating a free-floating segment that moves paradoxically during respiration, severely impairing ventilation.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q23">
            <div class="question-text">23. Cleft palate is a congenital disorder where the hard palate fails to fully fuse. The primary bones involved in forming the hard palate that fail to unite are the maxilla and which other bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q23" value="a"> Zygomatic bones</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q23" value="b" data-correct="true"> Palatine bones</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q23" value="c"> Vomer</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q23" value="d"> Ethmoid bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp23">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The hard palate is formed by the palatine processes of the <span class="correct-term">Maxillae</span> anteriorly and the horizontal plates of the <span class="correct-term">Palatine bones</span> posteriorly. Cleft palate results from the incomplete fusion of these components.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q24">
            <div class="question-text">24. Sinusitis is the inflammation of the mucous membrane lining the paranasal sinuses (Section 7.13). Due to the close proximity and drainage pathway, which sinus is typically the most frequently affected by infection?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q24" value="a"> Sphenoid sinus</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q24" value="b"> Ethmoid air cells</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q24" value="c" data-correct="true"> Maxillary sinus</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q24" value="d"> Frontal sinus</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp24">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Maxillary sinus</span> is the largest and most frequently infected sinus. Its drainage ostium is located near the roof of the sinus, making gravitational drainage difficult when the head is upright.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q25">
            <div class="question-text">25. Severe trauma to the midface can result in a fracture that separates the maxilla from the rest of the skull, leading to facial instability. These are classified as:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q25" value="a"> Blowout fractures</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q25" value="b"> Mandibular fractures</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q25" value="c" data-correct="true"> Le Fort fractures</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q25" value="d"> Tripod fractures</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp25">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Le Fort fractures</span> are a classification system for midface fractures involving the maxilla and surrounding structures (nasal, zygomatic, pterygoid plates).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q26">
            <div class="question-text">26. In the context of Temporomandibular Joint (TMJ) Dysfunction, which specific part of the Mandible articulates with the Mandibular Fossa of the Temporal bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q26" value="a"> Coronoid process</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q26" value="b"> Angle of the mandible</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q26" value="c" data-correct="true"> Mandibular condyle</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q26" value="d"> Mental protuberance</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp26">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Mandibular condyle</span> (or head of the mandible) is the component of the lower jaw that forms the articulation with the temporal bone to create the TMJ.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q27">
            <div class="question-text">27. Following a severe head injury, the presence of bruising over the mastoid process (behind the ear) is a clinical sign highly indicative of a fracture involving the base of the skull, specifically the temporal bone. This sign is called:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q27" value="a"> Raccoon eyes</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q27" value="b" data-correct="true"> Battle's sign</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q27" value="c"> Trousseau's sign</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q27" value="d"> Cushing's triad</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp27">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Battle's sign</span> is the ecchymosis (bruising) seen over the mastoid process, caused by leakage of blood from fractured vessels in the temporal bone/base of the skull.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q28">
            <div class="question-text">28. An epidural hematoma is often caused by rupture of the Middle Meningeal Artery. A fracture in which thin bone of the lateral skull frequently causes this rupture?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q28" value="a"> Occipital bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q28" value="b" data-correct="true"> Temporal bone (Pterion region)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q28" value="c"> Frontal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q28" value="d"> Vomer</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp28">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Middle Meningeal Artery runs deep to the thin bone of the <span class="correct-term">Temporal bone</span>, particularly near the Pterion, making it highly vulnerable to laceration by skull fracture, leading to a rapidly expanding epidural hematoma.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q29">
            <div class="question-text">29. A newborn is diagnosed with an abnormal head shape due to the premature fusion of one or more cranial sutures. What is the clinical name for this condition?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q29" value="a"> Hydrocephalus</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q29" value="b" data-correct="true"> Craniosynostosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q29" value="c"> Microcephaly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q29" value="d"> Anencephaly</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp29">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Craniosynostosis</span> is the clinical term for the premature fusion of cranial sutures, which restricts brain growth perpendicular to the fused suture and causes skull deformity.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q30">
            <div class="question-text">30. Pituitary tumors, particularly those causing Acromegaly, can enlarge the pituitary gland. This enlargement often leads to radiographic changes (enlargement) in which feature of the sphenoid bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q30" value="a"> Foramen lacerum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q30" value="b" data-correct="true"> Sella Turcica (Hypophyseal Fossa)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q30" value="c"> Pterygoid processes</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q30" value="d"> Optic canal</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp30">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The pituitary gland rests in the <span class="correct-term">Hypophyseal Fossa</span>, which is the central depression within the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone. Pituitary tumors commonly cause radiographic enlargement of this area.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q31">
            <div class="question-text">31. An infection of the middle ear (otitis media) can spread to the air cells within the adjacent bone, causing severe pain and swelling behind the ear. This condition is called:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q31" value="a"> Temporal lobe abscess</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q31" value="b" data-correct="true"> Mastoiditis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q31" value="c"> Sinusitis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q31" value="d"> Osteomyelitis of the frontal bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp31">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Mastoiditis</span> is the infection and inflammation of the mastoid air cells within the mastoid process of the temporal bone, often a complication of untreated otitis media.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q32">
            <div class="question-text">32. Trigeminal Neuralgia involves severe facial pain. The mandibular division of the Trigeminal nerve (V3) exits the base of the skull through which foramen of the sphenoid bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q32" value="a"> Foramen rotundum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q32" value="b" data-correct="true"> Foramen ovale</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q32" value="c"> Superior orbital fissure</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q32" value="d"> Foramen spinosum</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp32">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The three divisions of the Trigeminal nerve exit the skull via distinct foramina: V1 (Ophthalmic) via Superior Orbital Fissure, V2 (Maxillary) via Foramen Rotundum, and V3 (Mandibular) via the <span class="correct-term">Foramen Ovale</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q33">
            <div class="question-text">33. The Internal Carotid Artery (ICA) enters the skull through a canal within the petrous part of the temporal bone. Which bone feature houses the ICA?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q33" value="a"> Foramen magnum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q33" value="b" data-correct="true"> Carotid canal</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q33" value="c"> Jugular foramen</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q33" value="d"> Foramen lacerum</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp33">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Carotid canal</span> is the tortuous passage within the temporal bone that transmits the Internal Carotid Artery into the cranial cavity.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q34">
            <div class="question-text">34. Compression of the nerves of the cauda equina, typically due to a massive central lumbar disc herniation or trauma, can cause a medical emergency known as Cauda Equina Syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by severe bilateral sciatica, saddle anesthesia, and:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q34" value="a"> Unilateral foot drop only</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q34" value="b"> Only mild lower back pain</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q34" value="c" data-correct="true"> Bladder and bowel dysfunction (loss of control)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q34" value="d"> Isolated neck stiffness</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp34">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The hallmark symptoms of Cauda Equina Syndrome, beyond pain and numbness, include acute <span class="correct-term">bladder and bowel dysfunction</span> (urinary retention and incontinence), making it a surgical emergency.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q35">
            <div class="question-text">35. A patient presents with numbness and tingling in the hand, diagnosed as Thoracic Outlet Syndrome. This is sometimes caused by a rare congenital anomaly where a small, extra rib arises from which cervical vertebra?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q35" value="a"> C1 (Atlas)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q35" value="b" data-correct="true"> C7</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q35" value="c"> T1</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q35" value="d"> T12</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp35">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> A <span class="correct-term">Cervical Rib</span> is a supernumerary rib originating from the transverse process of <span class="correct-term">C7</span>. It can compress the brachial plexus and/or the subclavian artery, causing Thoracic Outlet Syndrome symptoms.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q36">
            <div class="question-text">36. A fracture of the hyoid bone is relatively rare but highly significant in forensic pathology. As mentioned in the textbook (Section 7.15), the hyoid bone is unique because:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q36" value="a"> It is part of the vertebral column</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q36" value="b" data-correct="true"> It does not articulate with any other bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q36" value="c"> It is the only bone found in the neck</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q36" value="d"> It is a sesamoid bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp36">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The text states: "<span class="correct-term">The hyoid bone is the only bone of the body that does not articulate with any other bone</span>" (Section 7.15). Its fracture is highly suggestive of manual strangulation.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q37">
            <div class="question-text">37. Clinically, the Anterior Fontanelle is the largest fontanelle. It normally closes at approximately what age range?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q37" value="a"> At birth</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q37" value="b"> 2 to 4 months</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q37" value="c" data-correct="true"> 18 to 24 months</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q37" value="d"> 5 to 7 years</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp37">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Anterior Fontanelle, located at the junction of the coronal and sagittal sutures, typically closes much later than the posterior fontanelle, usually between <span class="correct-term">18 and 24 months</span> of age.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q38">
            <div class="question-text">38. Pregnant women often develop an exaggerated lumbar curvature to compensate for the weight gain in the anterior abdomen, helping maintain the center of gravity. This abnormal increase in the lumbar curve is known as:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q38" value="a"> Scoliosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q38" value="b" data-correct="true"> Lordosis (Swayback)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q38" value="c"> Kyphosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q38" value="d"> Ankylosis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp38">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Lordosis</span> is the exaggerated anterior curvature (swayback) that is characteristic of the lumbar spine, which is increased in pregnancy to maintain balance.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q39">
            <div class="question-text">39. A rheumatologic disease characterized by chronic inflammation of the spinal joints, leading to fusion of the vertebrae and a characteristic 'bamboo spine' appearance on X-ray, is:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q39" value="a"> Rheumatoid Arthritis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q39" value="b" data-correct="true"> Ankylosing Spondylitis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q39" value="c"> Gout</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q39" value="d"> Systemic Lupus Erythematosus</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp39">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Ankylosing Spondylitis</span> is a chronic inflammatory disease that primarily affects the sacroiliac joints and the spine, leading to the ossification of spinal ligaments and fusion of the vertebral bodies (syndesmophytes), creating the 'bamboo spine' appearance.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q40">
            <div class="question-text">40. Based on the mechanical stress they endure, which region of the vertebral column is the site of the majority of herniated intervertebral discs (Section 7.24)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q40" value="a"> Cervical region</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q40" value="b" data-correct="true"> Lumbar region</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q40" value="c"> Thoracic region</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q40" value="d"> Sacral region</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp40">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The text states: "<span class="correct-term">Most herniated discs occur in the lumbar region because it bears most of the body weight and most flexing and bending occur there</span>" (Section 7.24).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q41">
            <div class="question-text">41. Severely increased intracranial pressure (ICP) can force the cerebellum's tonsils downward through the largest foramen in the skull base, threatening the brainstem. This life-threatening event is known as tonsillar herniation through the:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q41" value="a"> Jugular foramen</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q41" value="b" data-correct="true"> Foramen magnum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q41" value="c"> Sphenoid fissure</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q41" value="d"> Foramen rotundum</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp41">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Foramen Magnum</span>, located in the occipital bone, is the large opening through which the brainstem is continuous with the spinal cord. Tonsillar herniation through this opening is fatal due to compression of vital centers.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q42">
            <div class="question-text">42. A fracture involving the cribriform plate of the Ethmoid bone may tear the olfactory nerves passing through it. What is the most common clinical consequence of this injury?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q42" value="a"> Deafness</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q42" value="b" data-correct="true"> Anosmia (loss of smell)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q42" value="c"> Diplopia (double vision)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q42" value="d"> Facial paralysis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp42">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The olfactory nerves (CN I) pass through the cribriform plate. Trauma to this area severs these delicate nerves, resulting in <span class="correct-term">Anosmia</span> (loss of the sense of smell).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q43">
            <div class="question-text">43. A common infection and abscess formation, known as a pilonidal cyst or sinus, is typically located near the distal end of the vertebral column, specifically over which bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q43" value="a"> L5 vertebra</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q43" value="b"> Ilium</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q43" value="c" data-correct="true"> Coccyx (Tailbone)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q43" value="d"> Sacrum, superior end</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp43">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> A pilonidal cyst is a small cyst or abscess that occurs in the crease of the buttocks near the <span class="correct-term">Coccyx</span> (tailbone). It is often recurrent and requires surgical drainage.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q44">
            <div class="question-text">44. A tumor or lesion near the Jugular Foramen, formed by the temporal and occipital bones, can compress multiple cranial nerves, leading to difficulty swallowing and hoarseness. Which group of nerves passes through this foramen?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q44" value="a"> CN I, II, III</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q44" value="b"> CN V, VI, VII</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q44" value="c" data-correct="true"> CN IX, X, XI (Glossopharyngeal, Vagus, Accessory)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q44" value="d"> CN XII only</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp44">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Glossopharyngeal (IX), Vagus (X), and Accessory (XI)</span> cranial nerves, along with the Internal Jugular Vein, all pass through the Jugular Foramen. Compression leads to deficits in pharyngeal and laryngeal function.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q45">
            <div class="question-text">45. True ribs are defined by their direct articulation with the sternum via their own costal cartilage. Which ribs are classified as True Ribs?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q45" value="a"> Ribs 1-5</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q45" value="b" data-correct="true"> Ribs 1-7</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q45" value="c"> Ribs 8-10</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q45" value="d"> Ribs 11-12</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp45">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">True Ribs (1-7)</span> connect directly to the sternum. False ribs (8-12) do not; 8-10 connect indirectly via costal cartilage fusion, and 11-12 are floating ribs.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q46">
            <div class="question-text">46. The textbook (Section 7.10) notes that the Mandible is the only movable skull bone, other than which other small bones?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q46" value="a"> Ethmoid bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q46" value="b" data-correct="true"> Auditory ossicles</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q46" value="c"> Vomer</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q46" value="d"> Zygomatic bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp46">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The text states: "<span class="correct-term">The mandible is the only movable skull bone, other than the auditory ossicles</span>" (Section 7.10), which are the malleus, incus, and stapes in the middle ear.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q47">
            <div class="question-text">47. A deviated septum, often causing breathing issues, is a common clinical condition. The nasal septum (Section 7.11) is formed primarily by the perpendicular plate of the Ethmoid bone and which other bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q47" value="a"> Nasal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q47" value="b"> Maxilla</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q47" value="c" data-correct="true"> Vomer</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q47" value="d"> Lacrimal bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp47">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The bony part of the nasal septum is formed primarily by the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone superiorly and the <span class="correct-term">Vomer</span> inferiorly.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q48">
            <div class="question-text">48. Which of the following bones is NOT one of the seven bones that contribute to the formation of the orbit (Section 7.12)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q48" value="a"> Frontal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q48" value="b"> Zygomatic bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q48" value="c" data-correct="true"> Temporal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q48" value="d"> Lacrimal bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp48">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The seven bones forming the orbit are Frontal, Sphenoid, Zygomatic, Maxilla, Lacrimal, Ethmoid, and Palatine. The main part of the <span class="correct-term">Temporal bone</span> does not directly contribute to the orbital walls.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q49">
            <div class="question-text">49. Bell's Palsy is characterized by sudden, temporary paralysis of the facial muscles. The Facial Nerve (CN VII) travels through and exits which bone of the skull to reach the face?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q49" value="a"> Occipital bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q49" value="b" data-correct="true"> Temporal bone (Stylomastoid Foramen)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q49" value="c"> Sphenoid bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q49" value="d"> Maxilla</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp49">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Facial Nerve (CN VII) traverses the petrous part of the <span class="correct-term">Temporal bone</span> through the internal acoustic meatus and facial canal, exiting the skull via the <span class="correct-term">Stylomastoid Foramen</span>, making it highly susceptible to compression or inflammation within this bony path.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q50">
            <div class="question-text">50. Movement at the atlanto-axial joint, where the Atlas (C1) pivots around the dens of the Axis (C2), is primarily responsible for which head movement (Section 7.18)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q50" value="a"> Nodding the head 'yes'</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q50" value="b" data-correct="true"> Shaking the head 'no' (Rotation)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q50" value="c"> Lateral bending of the neck</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q50" value="d"> Extreme hyperextension</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp50">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Atlanto-Axial joint is a pivot joint, allowing the <span class="correct-term">rotation</span> of the head (the "no" movement). The Atlanto-Occipital joint is primarily responsible for the nodding ("yes") movement.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q51">
            <div class="question-text">51. The stability of the craniovertebral junction (C1-C2) against excessive rotation is primarily provided by which pair of strong ligaments connecting the dens to the occipital bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q51" value="a"> Posterior Longitudinal Ligament</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q51" value="b" data-correct="true"> Alar Ligaments</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q51" value="c"> Ligamentum Flavum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q51" value="d"> Ligamentum Nuchae</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp51">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Alar Ligaments</span> connect the sides of the dens (C2) to the lateral margins of the foramen magnum (occipital bone). They are crucial stabilizers that limit excessive axial rotation.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q52">
            <div class="question-text">52. Hypertrophy (thickening) of which specific ligament of the vertebral column often contributes to acquired Lumbar Spinal Stenosis by encroaching upon the vertebral canal posteriorly?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q52" value="a"> Anterior Longitudinal Ligament (ALL)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q52" value="b" data-correct="true"> Ligamentum Flavum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q52" value="c"> Interspinous ligament</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q52" value="d"> Transverse ligament of Atlas</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp52">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Ligamentum Flavum</span> connects the laminae of adjacent vertebrae. Its thickening (hypertrophy), a common finding with aging, significantly narrows the spinal canal, causing Spinal Stenosis.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q53">
            <div class="question-text">53. The unique, upward-facing bony projections on the lateral borders of the superior surface of cervical vertebral bodies (C3-C7) are the Uncinate Processes. They form the joints of Luschka, which commonly contribute to:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q53" value="a"> Chronic Lumbar Lordosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q53" value="b"> Atlanto-occipital instability</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q53" value="c" data-correct="true"> Cervical Radiculopathy (nerve root compression)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q53" value="d"> Primary Coccydynia</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp53">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Osteophytes (bone spurs) often form at the joints of Luschka (or unconvertible joints), leading to narrowing of the intervertebral foramen, which commonly causes compression of cervical nerve roots (<span class="correct-term">Cervical Radiculopathy</span>).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q54">
            <div class="question-text">54. A congenital chest wall deformity where the sternum and costal cartilages grow abnormally inward, resulting in a pronounced indentation of the chest, is clinically termed:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q54" value="a"> Barrel chest</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q54" value="b" data-correct="true"> Pectus Excavatum (Funnel chest)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q54" value="c"> Pectus Carinatum (Pigeon chest)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q54" value="d"> Flail chest</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp54">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Pectus Excavatum</span> is a concave, sunken appearance of the sternum. While often cosmetic, severe cases can compromise heart and lung function due to limited space.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q55">
            <div class="question-text">55. The clinical condition Costochondritis is characterized by inflammation and tenderness, often mimicking heart pain, localized primarily to which joint structure?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q55" value="a"> Intervertebral disc (Thoracic)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q55" value="b" data-correct="true"> Costochondral and/or Costosternal joints</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q55" value="c"> Atlanto-occipital joint</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q55" value="d"> Zygapophyseal joints (Facet joints)</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp55">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Costochondritis</span> is the inflammation of the cartilage that connects the ribs to the sternum (<span class="correct-term">costochondral joints</span>) or the joints between the cartilage and the sternum (<span class="correct-term">costosternal joints</span>).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q56">
            <div class="question-text">56. The distinguishing feature of typical thoracic vertebrae that allows them to articulate with the ribs is the presence of:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q56" value="a"> Transverse foramen</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q56" value="b" data-correct="true"> Costal facets (for the head and tubercle of the rib)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q56" value="c"> Mammillary processes</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q56" value="d"> Large, rectangular spinous processes</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp56">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Costal facets</span> are specialized articular surfaces on the vertebral bodies and transverse processes of thoracic vertebrae for articulation with the ribs.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q57">
            <div class="question-text">57. Pain arising from the Sacroiliac (SI) joint, which connects the sacrum to the ilium, is typically referred to which area?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q57" value="a"> The neck and shoulder</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q57" value="b"> The knee joint</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q57" value="c" data-correct="true"> The buttock and posterior thigh</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q57" value="d"> The anterior abdominal wall</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp57">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Dysfunction or inflammation of the <span class="correct-term">Sacroiliac (SI) joint</span> is a common cause of lower back pain, which frequently radiates into the buttock and sometimes the posterior thigh (pseudo-sciatica).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q58">
            <div class="question-text">58. Chronic pain localized to the coccyx (tailbone), often aggravated by sitting, is known as Coccydynia. This is frequently due to trauma (a fall) or hypermobility/instability of which articulation?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q58" value="a"> L5-S1 intervertebral joint</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q58" value="b"> Sacroiliac joint</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q58" value="c" data-correct="true"> Sacrococcygeal joint</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q58" value="d"> Ischial tuberosity</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp58">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Coccydynia</span> is pain originating specifically from the <span class="correct-term">Sacrococcygeal joint</span> and surrounding soft tissues, often caused by a backwards fall onto the buttocks.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q59">
            <div class="question-text">59. The Vertebral Arteries, essential for posterior brain circulation, ascend through the cervical spine by passing through the foramina within the transverse processes of which vertebrae (typically)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q59" value="a"> C1 only</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q59" value="b"> T1 to T6</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q59" value="c" data-correct="true"> C1 through C6</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q59" value="d"> L1 to L5</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp59">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Vertebral Arteries typically enter the transverse foramen of <span class="correct-term">C6</span> and ascend through the foramina of C5, C4, C3, C2, and C1 before entering the skull.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q60">
            <div class="question-text">60. Intervertebral discs are reinforced anteriorly by the Anterior Longitudinal Ligament (ALL). Due to the ALL's strength and the relative weakness of the Posterolateral annulus, disc herniation occurs most frequently in which direction?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q60" value="a"> Directly Anteriorly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q60" value="b"> Directly Posteriorly (Central)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q60" value="c" data-correct="true"> Posterolaterally</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q60" value="d"> Vertically (into the vertebral body)</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp60">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Herniation is most common in the <span class="correct-term">Posterolateral</span> direction because the Posterior Longitudinal Ligament only weakly reinforces this area, leading to compression of the exiting spinal nerve root.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q61">
            <div class="question-text">61. Which ligament extends the full length of the vertebral column along the anterior surface of the vertebral bodies, primarily functioning to prevent excessive hyperextension of the spine?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q61" value="a"> Supraspinous ligament</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q61" value="b"> Posterior Longitudinal Ligament (PLL)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q61" value="c" data-correct="true"> Anterior Longitudinal Ligament (ALL)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q61" value="d"> Ligamentum Flavum</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp61">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Anterior Longitudinal Ligament (ALL)</span> is a broad, strong band that covers the anterior aspects of the vertebral bodies and discs, limiting hyperextension.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q62">
            <div class="question-text">62. The Pterion, a weak area on the side of the skull where the frontal, parietal, temporal, and sphenoid bones meet, is clinically significant because of the close proximity of which major vessel?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q62" value="a"> Internal Carotid Artery</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q62" value="b" data-correct="true"> Middle Meningeal Artery</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q62" value="c"> Vertebral Artery</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q62" value="d"> Maxillary Artery</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp62">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> A blow to the thin bone at the <span class="correct-term">Pterion</span> often results in a fracture that lacerates the underlying <span class="correct-term">Middle Meningeal Artery</span>, leading to a rapidly fatal epidural hematoma.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q63">
            <div class="question-text">63. A patient with Orbital Apex Syndrome presents with ophthalmoplegia (paralysis of eye movements) and facial numbness. This pathology involves structures passing through which opening in the sphenoid bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q63" value="a"> Optic canal</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q63" value="b"> Foramen rotundum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q63" value="c" data-correct="true"> Superior Orbital Fissure</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q63" value="d"> Inferior Orbital Fissure</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp63">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Superior Orbital Fissure</span> transmits multiple critical nerves (CN III, IV, VI, and the ophthalmic division of V) that control eye movement and sensation of the forehead and upper face.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q64">
            <div class="question-text">64. Which part of the Ethmoid bone is involved in forming the medial wall of the orbit and often fractures in trauma, leading to orbital emphysema (air under the skin)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q64" value="a"> Crista galli</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q64" value="b" data-correct="true"> Orbital plate (Lamina papyracea)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q64" value="c"> Cribriform plate</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q64" value="d"> Middle nasal concha</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp64">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Orbital plate (Lamina papyracea)</span> of the ethmoid bone is extremely thin. A fracture allows air from the ethmoid sinuses to leak into the orbit or surrounding tissues, causing orbital emphysema.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q65">
            <div class="question-text">65. Clear fluid leaking from the nose (Rhinorrhea) following a head injury is indicative of a Cerebrospinal Fluid (CSF) leak, strongly suggesting a fracture of which specific bone structure?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q65" value="a"> Maxillary sinus wall</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q65" value="b" data-correct="true"> Cribriform plate of the Ethmoid bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q65" value="c"> Vomer</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q65" value="d"> Sphenoid sinus</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp65">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Cribriform plate</span> separates the nasal cavity from the anterior cranial fossa. A fracture here allows CSF to drain through the nose (CSF Rhinorrhea).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q66">
            <div class="question-text">66. A "tripod fracture" involves the Zygomatic bone and Zygomatic arch. Clinically, a depressed Zygomatic arch fracture can impair jaw movement by impinging on which large muscle used for mastication?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q66" value="a"> Buccinator</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q66" value="b" data-correct="true"> Temporalis muscle</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q66" value="c"> Masseter muscle</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q66" value="d"> Orbicularis oris</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp66">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Temporalis muscle</span> passes deep to the zygomatic arch to attach to the coronoid process of the mandible. A depressed arch fragment can mechanically obstruct the muscle, limiting jaw opening.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q67">
            <div class="question-text">67. Due to their prominent position, which pair of facial bones is the most commonly fractured in facial trauma?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q67" value="a"> Zygomatic bones</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q67" value="b"> Maxillae</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q67" value="c" data-correct="true"> Nasal bones</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q67" value="d"> Palatine bones</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp67">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Nasal bones</span> are the most frequently fractured facial bones because they project anteriorly and are relatively thin, making them susceptible to direct impact.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q68">
            <div class="question-text">68. Eagle Syndrome is a rare condition characterized by recurrent throat pain and neck pain, sometimes radiating to the ear, caused by an abnormally elongated or fractured:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q68" value="a"> Mastoid Process</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q68" value="b" data-correct="true"> Styloid Process of the Temporal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q68" value="c"> Pterygoid Process of the Sphenoid bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q68" value="d"> Dens of the Axis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp68">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> In <span class="correct-term">Eagle Syndrome</span>, an elongated <span class="correct-term">Styloid Process</span> compresses the surrounding nerves and vessels (often CN V, VII, IX, X), causing the characteristic pain.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q69">
            <div class="question-text">69. The Occipital Condyles articulate with the superior articular facets of the Atlas (C1). This articulation is primarily responsible for which movement?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q69" value="a"> Rotation (shaking head 'no')</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q69" value="b" data-correct="true"> Flexion and Extension (nodding head 'yes')</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q69" value="c"> Lateral bending of the entire neck</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q69" value="d"> Translation (sliding forward)</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp69">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Atlanto-occipital joint</span> (Occipital Condyles on C1) is primarily a condyloid joint that facilitates the flexion and extension movement, resembling the nodding of the head ("yes").</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q70">
            <div class="question-text">70. Cleft lip, a common birth defect, results from the failure of fusion of the embryological processes that form the upper lip. The bony defect associated with this condition involves which bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q70" value="a"> Mandible</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q70" value="b" data-correct="true"> Maxilla</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q70" value="c"> Zygomatic bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q70" value="d"> Nasal bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp70">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Cleft lip and palate involve the bony structures of the upper jaw, primarily the alveolar process and the palatine process of the <span class="correct-term">Maxilla</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q71">
            <div class="question-text">71. Which crucial ligament is immediately posterior to the dens of C2, holding it firmly against the anterior arch of the Atlas (C1) and preventing dangerous anterior displacement of the dens into the spinal cord?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q71" value="a"> Ligamentum Nuchae</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q71" value="b" data-correct="true"> Transverse Ligament of the Atlas</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q71" value="c"> Tectorial membrane</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q71" value="d"> Posterior Longitudinal Ligament</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp71">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Transverse Ligament of the Atlas</span> is the strongest component of the cruciform ligament. Its rupture results in C1/C2 instability, a major risk for spinal cord injury.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q72">
            <div class="question-text">72. A patient with a severe cervical fracture is found to have a widening of the space between the dens and the anterior arch of the Atlas on X-ray. This is pathognomonic for rupture of which ligament?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q72" value="a"> Anterior Longitudinal Ligament</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q72" value="b" data-correct="true"> Transverse Ligament of the Atlas</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q72" value="c"> Supraspinous Ligament</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q72" value="d"> Alar Ligaments</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp72">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The space (ADI: atlanto-dens interval) is held constant by the <span class="correct-term">Transverse Ligament of the Atlas</span>. Widening this space confirms instability and rupture of this ligament, a critical neurological threat.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q73">
            <div class="question-text">73. While the spinal cord in adults typically ends at L1/L2, in newborns and infants, the spinal cord extends lower. Which lumbar level is the safest common landmark for Lumbar Puncture in pediatric patients?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q73" value="a"> L1/L2</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q73" value="b"> T12/L1</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q73" value="c" data-correct="true"> L4/L5 interspace</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q73" value="d"> S1/S2</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp73">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Although the cord terminates lower in children, the <span class="correct-term">L4/L5 interspace</span> remains the safest landmark (palpable via the iliac crests) as it is well below the conus medullaris, even if the cord extends slightly lower than the adult L1/L2 level.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q74">
            <div class="question-text">74. A stress fracture involving the narrow portion of the vertebral arch between the superior and inferior articular processes is called:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q74" value="a"> Spondylolisthesis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q74" value="b" data-correct="true"> Spondylolysis (Fracture of the Pars Interarticularis)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q74" value="c"> Spinal Stenosis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q74" value="d"> Discitis</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp74">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Spondylolysis</span> is specifically a fracture or defect in the <span class="correct-term">pars interarticularis</span>, often seen in athletes performing repetitive extension movements (e.g., gymnasts).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q75">
            <div class="question-text">75. Radiographically, a small invagination or herniation of the nucleus pulposus vertically through the endplate into the body of the adjacent vertebra is known as a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q75" value="a"> Herniated Nucleus Pulposus (HNP)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q75" value="b" data-correct="true"> Schmorl's Node</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q75" value="c"> Osteophyte</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q75" value="d"> Vertebral Hemangioma</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp75">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Schmorl's Nodes</span> represent a vertical herniation of the disc material (nucleus pulposus) into the spongy bone of the vertebral body.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q76">
            <div class="question-text">76. A severe fracture type resulting from high-energy axial compression, where the vertebral body is crushed in all directions and fragments are retropulsed into the spinal canal, is termed a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q76" value="a"> Wedge fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q76" value="b" data-correct="true"> Burst fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q76" value="c"> Chance fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q76" value="d"> Compression fracture</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp76">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> A <span class="correct-term">Burst fracture</span> involves severe comminution and outward displacement of the fractured bone, carrying a high risk of spinal cord injury due to fragments entering the canal.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q77">
            <div class="question-text">77. A stable fracture caused by sudden, forceful flexion and muscle contraction, resulting in an oblique fracture through the spinous process (most commonly C6 or C7), is known as a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q77" value="a"> Hangman's fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q77" value="b"> Jefferson fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q77" value="c" data-correct="true"> Clay-Shoveler's fracture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q77" value="d"> Teardrop fracture</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp77">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Clay-Shoveler's fracture</span> is an avulsion fracture of a lower cervical spinous process (C6 or C7), originally described in workers shoveling heavy materials.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q78">
            <div class="question-text">78. Before an individual meets the criteria for Osteoporosis, a less severe loss of bone density that increases fracture risk is diagnosed clinically as:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q78" value="a"> Osteoarthritis</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q78" value="b"> Osteogenesis Imperfecta</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q78" value="c" data-correct="true"> Osteopenia</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q78" value="d"> Rickets</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp78">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Osteopenia</span> is defined as bone density that is lower than normal peak density but not low enough to be classified as osteoporosis.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q79">
            <div class="question-text">79. A congenital variation where a supernumerary (extra) rib articulates with a lumbar vertebra, typically L1, is known as a:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q79" value="a"> Floating rib</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q79" value="b"> Forked rib</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q79" value="c" data-correct="true"> Lumbar rib</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q79" value="d"> Cervical rib</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp79">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> Similar to a cervical rib, a <span class="correct-term">Lumbar rib</span> is a rare developmental anomaly where a rib forms on a lumbar vertebra, usually L1.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q80">
            <div class="question-text">80. The Superior Nuchal Line on the occipital bone serves as a major attachment point for which large, superior back and neck muscle, crucial for shrugging the shoulders and extending the head?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q80" value="a"> Sternocleidomastoid</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q80" value="b" data-correct="true"> Trapezius muscle</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q80" value="c"> Platysma</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q80" value="d"> Deltoid muscle</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp80">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Superior Nuchal Line</span> is a key attachment site for the large <span class="correct-term">Trapezius muscle</span>, as well as the sternocleidomastoid muscle.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q81">
            <div class="question-text">81. Chronic Maxillary Sinusitis is often related to poor drainage. The Maxillary Sinus drains into the middle meatus of the nasal cavity through an ostium located where relative to the sinus floor?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q81" value="a"> Near the floor (gravity-assisted)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q81" value="b" data-correct="true"> Near the roof (superiorly)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q81" value="c"> Posteriorly, near the pterygoid plates</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q81" value="d"> Into the frontal sinus</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp81">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The drainage ostium of the <span class="correct-term">Maxillary Sinus</span> is located high up, near its roof. This necessitates ciliary action to push mucus upwards against gravity, making drainage inefficient when inflamed.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q82">
            <div class="question-text">82. The Palatine bones contribute to the formation of the hard palate and which other major facial cavity?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q82" value="a"> Temporal fossa</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q82" value="b"> Auditory canal</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q82" value="c" data-correct="true"> Floor of the Orbit</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q82" value="d"> Mastoid air cells</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp82">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Palatine bones contribute to the walls of three cavities: the nasal cavity, the mouth (hard palate), and a small part of the <span class="correct-term">Floor of the Orbit</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q83">
            <div class="question-text">83. The second division of the Trigeminal Nerve (V2, Maxillary nerve), responsible for sensation over the cheek, upper lip, and nasal cavity, exits the middle cranial fossa via which foramen?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q83" value="a"> Foramen Ovale</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q83" value="b" data-correct="true"> Foramen Rotundum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q83" value="c"> Superior Orbital Fissure</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q83" value="d"> Hypoglossal canal</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp83">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> V1 passes through the Superior Orbital Fissure, V2 passes through the <span class="correct-term">Foramen Rotundum</span>, and V3 passes through the Foramen Ovale (remember 'Standing Room Only' for S-R-O).</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q84">
            <div class="question-text">84. Which highly dense, specialized region of the Temporal bone contains the cochlea, vestibule, and the passageway for the Internal Carotid Artery?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q84" value="a"> Squamous part</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q84" value="b" data-correct="true"> Petrous part</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q84" value="c"> Tympanic part</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q84" value="d"> Zygomatic process</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp84">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Petrous part</span> of the temporal bone is the hard, wedge-shaped ridge that houses the inner ear structures and the Carotid Canal.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q85">
            <div class="question-text">85. As blood leaves the sigmoid and inferior petrosal sinuses within the skull, they exit the Jugular Foramen and merge to form which large vessel?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q85" value="a"> Vertebral Vein</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q85" value="b" data-correct="true"> Internal Jugular Vein</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q85" value="c"> External Jugular Vein</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q85" value="d"> Internal Carotid Artery</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp85">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Internal Jugular Vein</span> begins at the Jugular Foramen, immediately upon receiving the contents of the Sigmoid Sinus, which drains most of the cranial cavity's blood.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q86">
            <div class="question-text">86. Paralysis and atrophy of the tongue muscles would suggest damage to the Hypoglossal Nerve (CN XII), which exits the cranial cavity through the Hypoglossal Canal located in which bone?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q86" value="a"> Sphenoid bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q86" value="b" data-correct="true"> Occipital bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q86" value="c"> Temporal bone</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q86" value="d"> Ethmoid bone</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp86">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Hypoglossal Canal</span>, which transmits the Hypoglossal Nerve (CN XII) to the tongue, is located within the <span class="correct-term">Occipital bone</span>, medial and superior to the occipital condyles.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q87">
            <div class="question-text">87. The Anterior Fontanelle is the soft spot at the meeting point of which two cranial sutures?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q87" value="a"> Lambdoid and Squamous</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q87" value="b" data-correct="true"> Coronal and Sagittal</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q87" value="c"> Sagittal and Lambdoid</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q87" value="d"> Squamous and Coronal</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp87">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Anterior Fontanelle (Bregma) is formed at the intersection of the midline <span class="correct-term">Sagittal Suture</span> and the bilateral <span class="correct-term">Coronal Suture</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q88">
            <div class="question-text">88. In contrast to the Anterior Fontanelle, the Posterior Fontanelle (at the junction of the Sagittal and Lambdoid sutures) typically closes much earlier, around what age?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q88" value="a"> 12 months</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q88" value="b" data-correct="true"> 2-3 months</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q88" value="c"> 5 years</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q88" value="d"> 6-12 years</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp88">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Posterior Fontanelle</span> (Lambda) typically closes very early in infancy, usually by <span class="correct-term">2-3 months</span> of age, sometimes even before birth.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q89">
            <div class="question-text">89. A congenital condition where the sutures of the skull close too soon, or where the brain fails to develop properly, leading to an abnormally small skull and brain size, is termed:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q89" value="a"> Hydrocephalus</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q89" value="b"> Macrocephaly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q89" value="c" data-correct="true"> Microcephaly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q89" value="d"> Plagiocephaly</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp89">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Microcephaly</span> literally means "small head" and is a severe neurological condition associated with restricted brain growth.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q90">
            <div class="question-text">90. Battle's sign (bruising behind the ear) associated with a basilar skull fracture is caused by the rupture of blood vessels leading to blood tracking from the middle cranial fossa and leaking out through which region?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q90" value="a"> Sphenoid sinus</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q90" value="b" data-correct="true"> Mastoid air cells</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q90" value="c"> Ethmoid sinuses</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q90" value="d"> Optic canal</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp90">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The blood from the temporal bone fracture tracks through the <span class="correct-term">Mastoid air cells</span> to the subcutaneous tissue overlying the mastoid process, causing the visible bruising.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q91">
            <div class="question-text">91. A condition similar to Costochondritis but characterized by a palpable, painful swelling of one or more costal cartilages (typically Ribs 2 or 3) is specifically called:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q91" value="a"> Pectus Excavatum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q91" value="b" data-correct="true"> Tietze Syndrome</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q91" value="c"> Flail Chest</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q91" value="d"> Sternoclavicular Dislocation</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp91">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Tietze Syndrome</span> is a distinct, rarer condition characterized by the same costochondral inflammation as costochondritis but always includes a localized, non-suppurative swelling.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q92">
            <div class="question-text">92. The false ribs (Ribs 8-10) attach to the costal cartilage immediately above them. Which set of ribs is correctly defined as "floating" and has no anterior cartilaginous attachment at all?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q92" value="a"> Ribs 6 and 7</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q92" value="b"> Ribs 8, 9, and 10</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q92" value="c" data-correct="true"> Ribs 11 and 12</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q92" value="d"> Ribs 1 and 2</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp92">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Ribs 11 and 12</span> are classified as "Floating Ribs" because their costal cartilages are rudimentary and do not attach to the sternum or costal cartilage of higher ribs.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q93">
            <div class="question-text">93. The Sternal Angle (Angle of Louis) is often used clinically as a guide to locate the transverse plane that passes through which intervertebral disc?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q93" value="a"> C7/T1</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q93" value="b" data-correct="true"> T4/T5</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q93" value="c"> T10/T11</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q93" value="d"> L1/L2</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp93">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The Sternal Angle is a surface landmark that corresponds internally to the plane passing between the T4 and T5 vertebrae (<span class="correct-term">T4/T5 disc</span>), which is the boundary between the superior and inferior mediastinum.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q94">
            <div class="question-text">94. The anatomical feature common to nearly all typical vertebrae (excluding C1 and C2) is the presence of a central supportive mass anteriorly, called the:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q94" value="a"> Spinous Process</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q94" value="b" data-correct="true"> Body (Centrum)</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q94" value="c"> Lamina</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q94" value="d"> Transverse Process</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp94">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Vertebral Body (Centrum)</span> is the large, anterior, cylindrical part of the vertebra, primarily responsible for bearing the body's weight.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q95">
            <div class="question-text">95. The four coccygeal vertebrae (Co1–Co4) typically fuse into a single bone. When does this fusion process usually complete?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q95" value="a"> At birth</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q95" value="b"> By age 5</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q95" value="c"> During puberty</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q95" value="d" data-correct="true"> In later adult life (often not complete until middle age)</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp95">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The bones of the <span class="correct-term">Coccyx</span> start fusing during early adulthood, but the process may not be fully complete until middle age, or sometimes the segments remain separate.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q96">
            <div class="question-text">96. The Sacral Hiatus, an inverted V-shaped opening at the inferior end of the sacral canal, is a key anatomical landmark used for the injection of anesthesia in which clinical procedure?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q96" value="a"> Lumbar Puncture</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q96" value="b" data-correct="true"> Caudal Epidural Anesthesia</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q96" value="c"> Joint aspiration</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q96" value="d"> Discography</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp96">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The <span class="correct-term">Sacral Hiatus</span> provides access to the caudal epidural space, which is targeted when administering <span class="correct-term">Caudal Epidural Anesthesia</span>, particularly during labor or for chronic low back pain.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q97">
            <div class="question-text">97. The most common direction of dislocation of the Temporomandibular Joint (TMJ), often occurring after a wide yawn or a blow to the jaw, is displacement of the mandibular condyle in which direction?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q97" value="a"> Posteriorly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q97" value="b" data-correct="true"> Anteriorly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q97" value="c"> Superiorly</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q97" value="d"> Medially</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp97">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> When the mouth opens widely, the mandibular condyle moves forward (translation). If it moves too far forward and locks in front of the articular eminence, it results in an <span class="correct-term">Anterior dislocation</span>, which is the most common TMJ dislocation.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q98">
            <div class="question-text">98. Which common spinal fracture mechanism involves a combination of flexion (bending forward) and an axial load, typically resulting in a collapse of the anterior aspect of the vertebral body?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q98" value="a"> Hyperextension injury</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q98" value="b" data-correct="true"> Flexion-compression injury</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q98" value="c"> Rotation-distraction injury</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q98" value="d"> Shear force injury</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp98">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> <span class="correct-term">Flexion-compression injury</span> is the biomechanical term for the mechanism that produces the common wedge-shaped <span class="correct-term">compression fracture</span>, often seen in falls onto the buttocks or osteoporosis.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q99">
            <div class="question-text">99. An intervertebral disc is composed of a tough, fibrous outer ring, and a soft, gelatinous core. These two parts are anatomically known as the:</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q99" value="a"> Endplate and Centrum</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q99" value="b"> Annulus Fibrosus and Lamina</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q99" value="c" data-correct="true"> Annulus Fibrosus and Nucleus Pulposus</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q99" value="d"> Ligamentum Flavum and Posterior Longitudinal Ligament</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp99">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The outer ring is the <span class="correct-term">Annulus Fibrosus</span>, which contains the inner, highly hydrated, gelatinous core, the <span class="correct-term">Nucleus Pulposus</span>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question-box" id="q100">
            <div class="question-text">100. The vertebral column has four main curves. Which two curves are classified as "primary curves" because they are present during fetal development (Section 7.16)?</div>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q100" value="a"> Cervical and Lumbar</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q100" value="b"> Lumbar and Sacral</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q100" value="c" data-correct="true"> Thoracic and Sacral</label>
            <label class="option-label"><input type="radio" name="q100" value="d"> Cervical and Thoracic</label>
            <div class="explanation" id="exp100">
                <p class="explanation-content"><strong>Explanation:</strong> The text states (Section 7.16): "The <span class="correct-term">thoracic and sacral curves</span> of the vertebral column are concave relative to the anterior of the body." These are the primary curves present at birth.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

