<p>During bone elongation at the epiphyseal plate, the first step is resting. This is when the chondrocytes in the epiphyseal plate are not actively dividing. The next step is proliferation, where the chondrocytes undergo rapid cell division and form stacks of cells. After proliferation, the chondrocytes undergo hypertrophication, where they enlarge and mature. Finally, calcification occurs, where the chondrocytes mineralize and form bone tissue. Therefore, the correct sequence of processes is resting, proliferation, hypertrophication, and calcification.</p>
